\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Two Types of Charge}
\begin{block}{The Law of Charge}
Electric charge causes objects to attract or repel each other.\\[0.2cm]
\begin{itemize}
\item Two types: \alert{positive} and \alert{negative}
\item Like charges \textbf{repel}
\item Unlike charges \textbf{attract}
\end{itemize}
\end{block}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\begin{exampleblock}{The Mental Model}
Charge is like magnetism, but more fundamental. North repels north, south repels south - but electric charges build everything.
\end{exampleblock}
\note{[P0] [THE REVELATION] "Electric charge - the property that makes objects attract or repel"\\\\
- Two types: positive and negative (named by Ben Franklin)\\\\
- Like charges repel: positive repels positive, negative repels negative\\\\
- Unlike charges attract: positive attracts negative\\\\
[P1] [THE CONNECTION - Kinetic Archetype] "Like two skaters pushing off each other - same charges repel"\\\\
[THE WONDER] This simple rule explains chemistry, electricity, technology}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Glass and Silk Demonstration}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,height=0.6\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig05.jpg}
\end{figure}

\pause
Glass rubbed with silk becomes \alert{positive}. Silk becomes \alert{negative}.
\note{[P0] "Classic demonstration from 1700s - rub glass rod with silk"\\\\
- Glass becomes positively charged\\\\
- Silk becomes negatively charged\\\\
- Panel a: opposite charges attract\\\\
- Panels b and c: like charges repel\\\\
[P1] "This is how scientists discovered two types of charge"\\\\
[THE HUMILITY] It took 2000 years from ancient Greeks noticing amber to understanding charge}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 The Carriers of Charge}
\begin{alertblock}{Civilian vs. Reality}
\textbf{Civilian:} "Charge is some mysterious fluid"\\
\textbf{Physicist:} "Charge is carried by fundamental particles"
\end{alertblock}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\textbf{The particles:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \alert{Electron}: carries negative charge ($-e$) \pause
\item \alert{Proton}: carries positive charge ($+e$) \pause
\item Fundamental unit: $e = 1.602 \times 10^{-19}$ C
\end{itemize}
\note{[P0] [THE CONFLICT] "For 2000 years, scientists thought charge was a mysterious fluid"\\\\
- William Gilbert proposed 'electrical fluid' in 1600s\\\\
- Debated for centuries\\\\
[P1] "1897: J.J. Thomson discovers the electron - the particle carrying negative charge"\\\\
[P2] "Protons carry positive charge, stuck in nucleus"\\\\
[P3] [THE REVELATION] "The fundamental unit: e equals 1.602 times 10 to the minus 19 coulombs"\\\\
[THE WONDER] Every electron in the universe carries exactly the same charge}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Atoms Are Neutral}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth,height=0.5\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig07.jpg}
\end{figure}

\pause
Rutherford's model: electrons orbit a tiny, dense nucleus of protons.\\
\textbf{Net charge = 0} (equal positive and negative)
\note{[P0] "Left: Thomson's plum-pudding model - electrons swimming in positive goo. WRONG."\\\\
- Right: Rutherford's nuclear model - electrons orbit tiny nucleus\\\\
[P1] "Atoms are electrically neutral - same number of protons and electrons"\\\\
- Protons in nucleus (positive)\\\\
- Electrons in orbits (negative)\\\\
[THE HUMILITY] Thomson was brilliant, but his model was destroyed by his own student Rutherford}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 How Much Charge?}
\begin{block}{The Coulomb (C)}
SI unit of electric charge.\\[0.2cm]
$e = 1.602 \times 10^{-19}$ C
\end{block}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\textbf{How many protons make +1.00 C?}

\pause
$$n = \frac{1.00 \text{ C}}{1.602 \times 10^{-19} \text{ C/proton}} = 6.25 \times 10^{18} \text{ protons}$$

\pause
\begin{exampleblock}{Imagine This...}
6.25 billion billion protons. That's more protons than stars in a million galaxies.
\end{exampleblock}
\note{[P0] [THE REVELATION] "The coulomb - named after Charles-Augustin de Coulomb"\\\\
- Fundamental charge: e equals 1.602 times 10 to minus 19 coulombs\\\\
[P1] "How many protons to make one coulomb?"\\\\
[P2] [ALGEBRA] "n equals one coulomb divided by e"\\\\
- "equals 6.25 times 10 to the 18 protons"\\\\
[P3] [THE WONDER] "More protons than stars in a million galaxies - yet one coulomb is tiny in electrical terms"\\\\
[ANSWER] 6.25 times 10 to 18 protons}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Millikan Oil-Drop Experiment}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth,height=0.45\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig08.jpg}
\end{figure}

\pause
Measured fundamental charge by balancing electric force against gravity.\\
Result: $e = -1.59 \times 10^{-19}$ C (within 1\% of modern value)
\note{[P0] "1909: Millikan and Fletcher measure fundamental charge"\\\\
- Spray fine oil mist between charged plates\\\\
- Balance electric force against gravity\\\\
- Measure charge on individual droplets\\\\
[P1] "Found charge comes in discrete units - multiples of e"\\\\
- Modern value: minus 1.602 times 10 to minus 19 C\\\\
[THE HUMILITY] Millikan took sole credit, coerced his student Fletcher. History reveals ugly truths about human nature, even in science}
\end{frame}

\section{Conservation of Charge}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 The Law That Cannot Be Broken}
\begin{block}{Conservation of Charge}
\begin{center}
\Large $\boxed{q_{\text{initial}} = q_{\text{final}}}$
\end{center}
Electric charge cannot be created or destroyed.
\end{block}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\begin{exampleblock}{The Accounting Rule}
Charge is like money in a closed economy. It moves around, but the total never changes.
\end{exampleblock}
\note{[P0] [THE REVELATION] "Conservation of charge - one of the most fundamental laws in physics"\\\\
[ALGEBRA] "q-initial equals q-final"\\\\
- Charge cannot be created or destroyed\\\\
- Only transferred from one object to another\\\\
[P1] [THE CONNECTION - Digital Archetype] "Like a conservation law in a game engine - total resources constant, just redistributed"\\\\
[THE WONDER] This law has never been violated. Ever. In any experiment.}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Attempt: Conservation Problem}
\textbf{Try this on your own (3 min, silent):}

Two metal spheres initially have $+4$ C and $+8$ C of charge. After they touch, the blue sphere has $+10$ C.

\vspace{0.3cm}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth,height=0.3\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig12.jpg}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Initial: blue $= +4$ C, red $= +8$ C
\item Final: blue $= +10$ C
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Find:} Final charge on red sphere

\vspace{0.2cm}
\textit{Work individually. It's okay to get stuck.}
\note{[THE CHALLENGE] Can you find the missing charge using conservation?\\\\
[TIMING] 3-4 min SILENT individual work\\\\
[SAY] "Try this on your own. Use conservation of charge. Show your algebra."\\\\
- NO HINTS - let them struggle productively\\\\
- Walk around but don't help yet\\\\
- Note who uses conservation correctly}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Compare: Conservation Problem}
\textbf{Turn and talk (2 min):}

\begin{enumerate}
\item Share your approach with your partner
\item What equation did you use?
\item How did you solve for the red sphere's charge?
\end{enumerate}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\alert{Name wheel:} One pair share your approach (not your answer).
\note{- 2-3 min pair discussion\\\\
- Circulate and listen for approaches\\\\
- Name wheel: call a pair to share\\\\
- Listen for: did they use q-initial equals q-final?\\\\
- EXPECTED APPROACH: total before equals total after, solve for q-red\\\\
[THE CONNECTION] This is accounting - track where charge goes}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Reveal: Solution}
\textbf{Self-correct in a different color:}

\textbf{Strategy:} Use conservation of charge

\pause
$$q_{\text{initial}} = q_{\text{final}}$$

\pause
$$+4 \text{ C} + 8 \text{ C} = +10 \text{ C} + q_{\text{red}}$$

\pause
$$+12 \text{ C} = +10 \text{ C} + q_{\text{red}}$$

\pause
$$\boxed{q_{\text{red}} = +2 \text{ C}}$$

\pause
\textbf{Check:} Total before = $+12$ C. Total after = $+10 + 2 = +12$ C. âœ“
\note{- Walk through solution step by step\\\\
[P0] [ALGEBRA] "Conservation: q-initial equals q-final"\\\\
[P1] "Initial total: 4 plus 8 equals 12 coulombs"\\\\
[P2] "Final total: 10 plus q-red"\\\\
[P3] "Set them equal: 12 equals 10 plus q-red"\\\\
[P4] "Solve: q-red equals 2 coulombs"\\\\
[P5] "Check: 10 plus 2 equals 12. Conservation satisfied."\\\\
[ANSWER] q-red equals plus 2 coulombs\\\\
[THE WONDER] Charge redistributed but total unchanged - nature's accounting}
\end{frame}

\section{Conductors and Insulators}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Materials That Conduct}
\begin{block}{Conductor vs. Insulator}
\textbf{Conductor:} Charge moves easily (metals, copper, aluminum)\\
\textbf{Insulator:} Charge cannot move (rubber, plastic, glass)
\end{block}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\begin{exampleblock}{The Mental Model}
Conductors are like highways - electrons flow freely. Insulators are like walls - electrons stuck in place.
\end{exampleblock}
\note{[P0] [THE REVELATION] "Materials classified by ability to conduct charge"\\\\
- Conductors: metals with loosely bound outer electrons\\\\
- Charge moves easily through conductors\\\\
- Insulators: electrons held tightly to atoms\\\\
- Charge cannot move through insulators\\\\
[P1] [THE CONNECTION - Kinetic Archetype] "Like traffic - conductors are open roads, insulators are blocked"\\\\
[THE WONDER] Semiconductors (silicon) can be switched between conducting and insulating - that's how computer chips work}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 The Conductivity Scale}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,height=0.6\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig14-1.jpg}
\end{figure}

\pause
Resistivity measures how hard it is to move charge. Lower = better conductor.
\note{[P0] "Scale from conductors to semiconductors to insulators"\\\\
- Silver, copper: best conductors (lowest resistivity)\\\\
- Silicon: semiconductor (middle ground)\\\\
- Glass, rubber: insulators (highest resistivity)\\\\
[P1] "Note: scale is NOT linear - huge gaps between categories"\\\\
[THE CONNECTION - Digital Archetype] Semiconductors are the foundation of all digital technology - we control whether they conduct or insulate}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Charge Distribution}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth,height=0.5\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig14.jpg}
\end{figure}

\pause
\textbf{Conductor:} Charge spreads to outer surface (repulsion)\\
\textbf{Insulator:} Charge stays where placed (cannot move)
\note{[P0] "Add excess negative charge to conductor vs insulator"\\\\
- Panel a: conductor - electrons repel, spread to outer surface\\\\
- Panel b: insulator - electrons cannot move, stay put\\\\
[P1] [THE CONFLICT] "Like charges repel in BOTH cases, but only conductors allow movement"\\\\
[THE WONDER] This is why static shock happens - charge builds on insulator (your shoes), then suddenly transfers through conductor (your hand)}
\end{frame}

\section{Transfer of Charge}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Three Ways to Charge}
\begin{alertblock}{Key Insight}
Only \alert{negative} charge (electrons) moves in solids.\\
Protons are stuck in nuclei.
\end{alertblock}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\textbf{Three methods:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Contact:} Rubbing transfers electrons \pause
\item \textbf{Conduction:} Touching transfers charge \pause
\item \textbf{Induction:} Charge separation without touching
\end{itemize}
\note{[P0] [THE REVELATION] "Critical: only electrons move in solids"\\\\
- Protons stuck in nucleus, atoms stuck in place\\\\
- Electrons can jump between atoms\\\\
[P1] "Charging by contact: rub carpet, electrons transfer to shoes"\\\\
[P2] "Charging by conduction: touch doorknob, electrons jump"\\\\
[P3] "Charging by induction: nearby charge causes separation"\\\\
[THE WONDER] All of electronics based on controlled electron movement}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Charging by Contact}
\textbf{Example:} Walk across carpet on dry day

\vspace{0.3cm}
\begin{itemize}
\item Shoes rub carpet \pause
\item Electrons transfer from carpet to shoes \pause
\item You gain excess negative charge \pause
\item Touch doorknob - \alert{ZAP!} Electrons transfer to doorknob
\end{itemize}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\begin{exampleblock}{Real-World}
This is why you get shocked more on dry days. Humid air conducts charge away before buildup.
\end{exampleblock}
\note{[P0] "Classic static shock scenario"\\\\
[P1] "Shoes rub carpet - friction brings surfaces close"\\\\
[P2] "Electrons transfer from carpet to shoes - now you have excess negative"\\\\
[P3] "Excess electrons spread over your body (repulsion)"\\\\
[P4] "Touch metal doorknob - electrons jump to doorknob. ZAP!"\\\\
[THE CONNECTION - Kinetic Archetype] "Every step is friction - same as sliding down slide"\\\\
[THE HUMILITY] Humidity prevents this - water molecules in air conduct charge away}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Charging by Conduction}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth,height=0.45\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig16.jpg}
\end{figure}

\pause
\textbf{Top:} 100 electrons touch 50 electrons $\rightarrow$ charge equalizes to 75 each\\
\textbf{Bottom:} 100 protons touch 50 protons $\rightarrow$ electrons flow opposite direction
\note{[P0] "Conduction: charge transfer by direct contact"\\\\
- Top row: sphere with 100 excess electrons touches sphere with 50\\\\
- Electrons redistribute: 25 transfer, both end with 75\\\\
[P1] "Bottom row: sphere with 100 excess protons touches 50 excess protons"\\\\
- Actually electrons flow OTHER way: 25 electrons transfer to first sphere\\\\
- Cancels 25 protons, leaving 75 excess each\\\\
[THE REVELATION] Net effect same, but only electrons actually move in solids}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Polarization}
\begin{block}{Electric Polarization}
Charge separation within an object, creating positive region and negative region.\\
\textbf{Net charge still zero.}
\end{block}

\pause
\vspace{0.3cm}
\textbf{Example:} Child on slide (Figure 18.1)
\begin{itemize}
\item Excess positive charge on body
\item Positive charges repel each other
\item Spread to extremities (hair)
\item Hair strands repel $\rightarrow$ stand on end!
\end{itemize}
\note{[P0] [THE REVELATION] "Polarization: charge separates but total charge remains zero"\\\\
- Not creating charge, just pushing it around\\\\
[P1] "Child on slide: excess positive charge from friction"\\\\
- Positive charges repel each other\\\\
- Spread to extremities: hands, feet, hair\\\\
- Each hair strand has excess positive\\\\
- Strands repel each other - hair stands on end\\\\
[THE WONDER] This is temporary - charge leaks away to air, especially if humid}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Charging by Induction}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth,height=0.5\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig18.jpg}
\end{figure}

\pause
Charge objects \textit{without touching} by separating charge with nearby charged rod.
\note{[P0] "Induction: charging without contact"\\\\
- Panel a: two neutral spheres touching\\\\
- Panel b: bring positive rod near (don't touch)\\\\
- Negative charge attracted, positive repelled\\\\
- Panel c: separate spheres while rod nearby\\\\
- Panel d: remove rod - spheres now oppositely charged\\\\
[P1] [THE REVELATION] "Never touched, yet charged. Opposite charges attract, so they cluster near rod"\\\\
[THE WONDER] This is how you can charge objects without losing charge from the rod}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{18.1 Van de Graaff Generator}
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth,height=0.4\textheight,keepaspectratio]{phys11-electric-charge-fig19.jpg}
